    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-07-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-07-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="1230"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1230">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.512/327.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Consul
                            <persName type="to">Miller</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-07-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 10, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your July 8. Consul General Monterey has been instructed to take the matter up
                    with General Carranza at once and urgently insist that immediate orders be sent
                    to Tampico and Tuxpam authorities.</p>
                <pb facs="0863" n="747" xml:id="pg_747"/>
                <p>Is there not some responsible firm in Tampico carrying New York account through
                    which exchange arrangements could be perfected to meet local requirements? In
                    the absence of responsible commercial firm, could not some of the larger oil
                    interests be induced to establish such an arrangement. In that event could not
                    exchange rates be obtained from Mexico City or New York as necessity
                    required?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
